  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Is there any law in India to secretly report child labour?",
  "response": "In India, child labour is a serious issue, and there are laws in place to address it. The primary legislation governing child labour in India is the Child and Adolescent Labour (Prohibition and Regulation) Act, 1986, which was amended in 2016. This Act prohibits the employment of children below the age of 14 in all occupations and adolescents (14-18 years) in hazardous occupations and processes.\n\nTo report child labour, you can contact the following authorities:\n\n1. **Childline India Foundation**: You can call the toll-free number 1098, which is a 24-hour helpline for children in need of care and protection. They can help you report cases of child labour.\n\n2. **National Commission for Protection of Child Rights (NCPCR)**: You can file a complaint on their website (ncpcr.gov.in) or call their helpline number.\n\n3. **State Labour Department**: Each state has its own labour department, and you can contact them to report cases of child labour. You can find their contact information on the respective state government websites.\n\n4. **Police**: You can also report child labour to the local police station. They are required to take action under the Child and Adolescent Labour Act.\n\nWhile there isn't a specific law that allows for \"secretly\" reporting child labour, you can choose to remain anonymous when reporting to the above-mentioned authorities. It's important to provide as much detail as possible to help the authorities take appropriate action.\n\nRemember, reporting child labour is a crucial step in protecting the rights and well-being of children. If you suspect or witness child labour, do not hesitate to report it to the relevant authorities.",
